    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIn Nvim, `set iminsert=2` and `set imsearch=2` imsearch doesn't work because Nvim doesn't support building with xim or Windows IME like Vim. \n\nHowever, Vim also has `'imactivatefunc'` and `'imstatusfunc'` which allows users to customize IME support so `set iminsert=2 imsearch=2` can work in all platforms, even if Vim is not built with any IME or GUI support at all.\n\nUnfortunately, these 2 `'im*func'` options are not available in Nvim\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThese options should follow Vim behaviors",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "From https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/1708#issuecomment-2976048588\n\n> Our view/assupmtion in 2014 was that input-method is an OS or GUI feature. not something that can/should be arbitrated by Nvim.\n> \n> > Neovim could support IM auto-switching on all platforms\n> \n> We could consider supporting these `'im*'` features via a \"provider\" model. It looks like `'imactivatefunc'` and `'imstatusfunc'` fit that model, so I don't have a strong objection to restoring them. As long as it doesn't involve lots of platform-specific code or new build-time dependencies.\n\n> Vim implements `'imactivatefunc'` and `'imstatusfunc'` in `gui_xim.c`, even though these 2 options don't require Vim compiled with `+xim` or any GUI features at all [vim/vim#2349](https://github.com/vim/vim/pull/2349)\n\n",
